R plot annotation (mostly ggplot2)

Jamie Reilly, Ph.D.

2018-08-02

create a minimalist custom theme

Heres a minimalist custom theme for ggplot2. Ill add this to most of the plots to follow. It strips panel gridlines and all sorts of other default junk.

jamie.theme <- theme_bw() + theme(axis.line = element_line(colour = "black"), 
    panel.grid.minor = element_blank(), panel.grid.major = element_blank(), 
    panel.border = element_blank(), panel.background = element_blank(), legend.title = element_blank())

generate a scatterplot

ggplot2 can be a bit challenging WRT getting the axis formatted the way you want. Lets first generate a dataframe populated with random sampled data from 1-100 with replacement; plot the data (100 points). set the seed for reproducibility.

set.seed(999)
dat <- data.frame(replicate(2, sample(0:100, 100, rep = F)))
baseplot <- ggplot(dat, aes(X1, X2)) + geom_point(shape = 21, fill = "blue", 
    size = 2.3, alpha = 0.6) + jamie.theme
print(baseplot)

change axis scales and breaks

we need finer-grained notation on both axes. We can do this by adding breaks, every 10.

newplot <- baseplot + scale_x_continuous(breaks = seq(0, max(dat$X1), by = 10)) + 
    scale_y_continuous(breaks = seq(0, max(dat$X2), by = 10))
print(newplot)

changing the axis limits manually

xlim and ylim can cutoff data, be careful! here is what xlim=50 looks like

smaller <- baseplot + xlim(c(0, 50))
print(smaller)

zooming in on a specific range using coord_cartesian

this is sometimes useful. It zooms on a soecific range without cutting data

focused <- baseplot + coord_cartesian(xlim = c(0, 25), ylim = c(0, 50))
print(focused)
